Can you elaborate on the relationship between sorting and memory space in binary tree sort and how they affect each other?</s> 
Sure, in a binary tree sort, the elements are sorted in a tree data structure, where nodes are linked using left and right child pointers. Any new nodes added to the tree require additional memory space to store. As a result, more memory space is needed than in a linear sort, where elements are sorted in a list or array data structure. Therefore, if memory space is limited, a more memory-efficient data structure should be used. However, if memory space is not a concern, binary tree sort can be an advantageous sorting method due to its properties like fast insertion and deletion processes.
